Local Task Hub is a local first, dockerized, single-user application.

Always read these files before planning or implementing:

- AGENTS.md
- .gooseignore
- .goosehints
- MVP.md
- package.json
- docker-compose.yml
- components.json

Treat MVP.md as the product source of truth and AGENTS.md as the implementation policy.

Work in two distinct modes.

Planning mode:

- create or refine GitHub issues only
- do not implement code
- do not create branches or pull requests
- split work into small, reviewable issues
- include acceptance criteria and dependencies
- stay strictly within Phase 1

Implementation mode:

- work on exactly one GitHub issue at a time
- keep diffs small and reviewable
- do not broaden scope beyond the issue
- open a pull request when the issue is complete

Execution environment for this repository:

- this repository is now located on the Windows filesystem
- repository path: C:\Projects\local-task-hub
- do not assume a Linux or WSL shell
- do not assume POSIX commands are available
- do not use Linux paths such as /home/... or /mnt/c/...
- do not use WSL-specific command wrappers unless explicitly instructed
- prefer Windows-native shell commands and path handling
- always verify commands are compatible with the active shell before using them

Command guidance:

- do not assume `pwd` is available
- do not assume commands like `ls`, `cat`, `mv`, `cp`, `rm`, `touch`, `sed`, or `grep` are available
- prefer shell-appropriate commands, for example:
  - `cd` for current directory in cmd-based contexts
  - `Get-Location` in PowerShell contexts
- use Windows path syntax when referring to files in commands

Mandatory preflight before any edits:

- confirm the working directory is `C:\Projects\local-task-hub`
- confirm `node -v` works
- confirm `npm -v` works
- confirm `AGENTS.md` can be read
- confirm `MVP.md` can be read
- confirm the GitHub issue can be read successfully

If shell behavior is unclear or commands are not portable:

- stop and report the exact failing command
- do not guess shell semantics
- do not proceed with edits until command execution is reliable

If any preflight check fails:

- stop immediately
- report the environment blocker clearly
- do not edit files
- do not claim validation was performed

Hard stop rules:

- stop if shell quoting behaves inconsistently
- stop if commands succeed only intermittently
- stop if node or npm are unavailable
- stop if the repository path is treated as a Windows UNC path
- stop if required files or issue details cannot be read reliably
- do not continue with partial edits in an unstable environment

Technical defaults for this repository:

- Next.js App Router
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- shadcn/ui only for UI building blocks
- MySQL in Docker
- mysql2 or mysql2/promise for DB access
- no ORM
- desktop first
- dark mode required

UI guidance:

- prefer existing shadcn/ui patterns over custom primitives
- keep the interface calm, minimal, and information dense
- use accessible interaction patterns
- prefer Server Components by default
- use Client Components only where interaction requires them

Data guidance:

- keep SQL explicit and readable
- use parameterized queries only
- isolate database access in dedicated server-side modules
- do not introduce hidden architecture layers without need

Testing guidance:

- use Playwright for flows with meaningful interaction logic
- especially task creation, editing, filtering, time tracking, and persistence across reload
- do not claim tests passed unless they were actually run
- report exactly which validation commands were executed
- if validation is blocked by environment issues, report that explicitly

Scope guidance:

- no auth
- no multi-user support
- no cloud sync
- no third-party API integrations in Phase 1
- no drag and drop ordering in Phase 1
- no rich text editor
- no syntax highlighting
- no remote favicon fetching

When creating GitHub issues, apply labels consistently.

Rules:

- apply exactly one type label
- apply at least one area label
- apply exactly one priority label
- only use a status label when it adds real value
- use "epic" only for umbrella issues, never for normal implementation tasks
- use "needs-playwright" for issues with meaningful interaction logic
- do not invent new labels unless explicitly instructed

If a requirement is unclear, prefer the smaller and safer interpretation.
If a change feels architectural or broad, stop and reduce scope.
Never silently invent Phase 2 features inside a Phase 1 issue.
